    {
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "The relative size of per-category values that make up the total value are mapped to the angular sizes of the sectors.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "To ensure that the visualization is easy to read, design pie or donut charts with no more than 5-7 sectors. Sum any remaining values into an “Other” group if necessary, or consider",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "horizontal bar charts, which can scale to many bars, are easy to label with categories, and let users compare items more accurately.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Make sure that your data contains only positive values. Also, very small proportions may not be discernible in the chart, especially if an angular inset is specified.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor": "Create-a-pie-chart-with-sector-marks",
          "level": 3,
          "text": "Create a pie chart with sector marks",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "To visualize the ratio of values to the total that they collectively add up to, specify the values, most often ordered by decreasing value. If needed, add an “Other” group",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "as the last item.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code": [
            "let data = [",
            "    (name: \"Cachapa\", sales: 9631),",
            "    (name: \"Crêpe\", sales: 6959),",
            "    (name: \"Injera\", sales: 4891),",
            "    (name: \"Jian Bing\", sales: 2506),",
            "    (name: \"American\", sales: 1777),",
            "    (name: \"Dosa\", sales: 625),",
            "]",
            "",
            "var body: some View {",
            "    Chart(data, id: \\.name) { name, sales in",
            "        SectorMark(angle: .value(\"Value\", sales))",
            "            .foregroundStyle(by: .value(\"Product category\", name))",
            "    }",
            "}"
          ],
          "syntax": "swift",
          "type": "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "anchor": "Create-and-style-a-donut-chart-with-sector-marks",
          "level": 3,
          "text": "Create and style a donut chart with sector marks",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "The inner and outer radii can be customized for your design. A non-zero inner radius yields a donut chart.",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "A small angular inset helps accessibility and readability by adding contrast between sectors, which is useful for pie and donut charts.",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "Limit the size of the angular inset and corner radius to small values to avoid distorting the shape and relative size of the sectors.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code": [
            "var body: some View {",
            "    Chart(data, id: \\.name) { name, sales in",
            "        SectorMark(",
            "            angle: .value(\"Value\", sales),",
            "            innerRadius: .ratio(0.618),",
            "            outerRadius: .inset(10),",
            "            angularInset: 1",
            "        )",
            "        .cornerRadius(4)",
            "        .foregroundStyle(by: .value(\"Product category\", name))",
            "    }",
            "}"
          ],
          "syntax": "swift",
          "type": "codeListing"
        }
      ],
      "kind": "content"
    }
